[1
Date: Fri, 17 Sep 1999 10:05:26 -0600
From: Carol Meteyer <Carol_Meteyer@usgs.gov>

Neurotropic velogenic Newcastle disease virus (avian paramyxovirus-1)
consistently affects the cerebellum and spinal cord of cormorants with
neuronophagia of Purkinje cells and large neurons in the spinal cord as
well as gliosis (Meteyer, Docherty, et al. Diagnostic Findings in 1992
Epornitic of Neurotropic Velogenic Newcastle Disease in Double-crested
Cormorants from the Upper Midwestern United States. Avian Diseases
41:171-180, 1997). The virus isolated from the cormorants will cause
similar lesions in poultry. Similar lesions are also seen in pigeons
infected with paramyxovirus-1 of pigeons. Dr. David Swayne (USDA-ARS,
SPRL, Georgia) can give you information regarding similar lesions in
poultry infected with certain strains of highly pathogenic avian influenza.
--
Carol Meteyer, DVM. Diplomate ACVP
Wildlife Pathologist
USGS-BRD
National Wildlife Health Center
Madison, Wisconsin
e-mail: Carol_Meteyer@usgs.gov
