[2
Date: Fri, 17 Sep 1999 18:22:33 +0200
From: Roger Eeckels <Roger.Eeckels@med.kuleuven.ac.be>

This is to try and answer our excellent Moderator CHC's question as to
which other
infectious diseases (besides Nipah virus encephalitis) can affect the
cerebellum. In children --mostly toddlers-- acute cerebellar ataxia is a
rather rare but well-known disease. It is attributed to several
enteroviruses (coxsackieviruses A4, A7, A9, B3, B4, and echoviruses 6, 9,
and 16). The same condition also occurs as a complication of chickenpox
(varicella-zoster virus [VZV) and Epstein-Barr virus infections.
As I guess have most paediatricians, I have seen quite some cases. The
disease
usually and characteristically starts very abruptly. Recovery is mostly
complete, but I have known some children with permanent sequellae (mild
ataxia and even moderate mental retardation).
As far as I know, the condition never has been described in epidemic form.
There must be studies of acute cerebellar ataxia cases with modern medical
imaging techniques, but I haven't looked these up. Yet, to quote my not too
recent Harrison's (12th edition, ) "In some instances of VZV infection,
the cerebellar lesions are of the parainfectious, demyelinating type."
--
Roger Eeckels, MD, DTM&H
Emeritus professor of paediatrics
University of Leuven (Louvain)
Belgium
e-mail: Roger.Eeckels@med.kuleuven.ac.be
[I am not "excellent". I have bronchitis. I would hate infectious disease
save for the fact that they provide job security. - Mod.CHC
