[3
Date: Fri, 17 Sep 1999 19:30:28 -0400
From: Bruce C. Toney <btoney@capecod.net>

Good question... Neurosyphilis comes to mind for me also (a form of tabes
dorsalis); as well as opportunistic fungal infections with toxoplasma or
cryptococcus in immunocompromised individuals, especially those with the
HIV-AIDS related complex... perhaps campylobacter also? Infectious causes
of cerebellar ataxia with cerebellar lesions is a rare bird as far as I know.
--
Bruce Toney, MD
Pathology (retired)
e-mail: btoney@capecod.net
